{
  format: 1
  name: target-seed-data-on-update-unspecified
  suite: scenario
  spec: ["#evolution", "§20.1", "§13.13", "§9.1"]
  note: '''
    Spec gap. §20.1 describes migration purely in terms of `$old` (source
    state) and `.` (prospective target after compatible copies and `$from`),
    and never says how a *target package's own* `$data` seed participates in a
    root-application update. §13.13 defines a three-way seed merge, but only for
    MODULE updates; nothing extends it to the root app, and §9.1 seed semantics
    are written for genesis `create`, not `load`-time update.

    Concretely: version 1.0.0 seeds items/a with value "old". Version 1.1.0
    also declares `$data` for items/a with value "new" (a compatible
    definition change otherwise). Whether the post-update live value of
    items/a is "old" (migration copy of existing state wins), "new" (new seed
    overwrites), or a three-way merge outcome is not deducible from §20. The
    load itself succeeds; only the resulting value is unpinned.
  '''

  package: {
    $liasse: 1
    $app: "t.mig.seed@1.0.0"
    $model: {
      items: {
        $key: "id"
        id: "text"
        value: "text"
      }
      $public: {
        items: { $view: ".items { id, value }" }
      }
    }
    $data: {
      items: { a: { value: "old" } }
    }
  }

  steps: [
    { host_load: {
        package: {
          $liasse: 1
          $app: "t.mig.seed@1.1.0"
          $model: {
            items: {
              $key: "id"
              id: "text"
              value: "text"
            }
            $public: {
              items: { $view: ".items { id, value }" }
            }
          }
          $data: {
            items: { a: { value: "new" } }
          }
        }
      }
      expect: { outcome: ok, result: committed } }
    { watch: "public.items", id: "w1",
      expect_init: { outcome: unspecified } }
  ]
}
